  "datePublished": "2026-01-01",
  "description": "An event is a collection of outcomes from a probabilistic experiment — something that either happens or does not happen, and to which a probability can be assigned. When you roll a die, \u0026ldquo;rolling an even number\u0026rdquo; is an event: it is the set of outcomes {2,4,6}\\{2, 4, 6\\} within the sample space Ω={1,2,3,4,5,6}\\Omega = \\{1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6\\}. \u0026ldquo;Rolling a 3\u0026rdquo; is an event (the set {3}\\{3\\}). \u0026ldquo;Rolling a number less than 10\u0026rdquo; is an event (the entire sample space — it always happens). \u0026ldquo;Rolling a 7\u0026rdquo; is an event too (the empty set — it never happens).\n",
